omedies produce a ";critically proximate"; spectator who is capable of perceiving and organizing space and time differently. Combining close readings of films, archival research, film theory, and Latin American history, Mock Classicism rethinks classicism as a discourse that mediates and renders the world and argues that Latin American cinema became classical in distinct ways from Hollywood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aComedy filmszLatin AmericaxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszLatin Americay20th century. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and directionzLatin Americay20th century. 0aMotion pictureszLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aalternate history.  aarchival research.  acantinflas oscarito.  acomedians.  acomedic practice.  acultural significance.  aembodiment.  afilm comedies.  afilm theory.  afilms.  agrande otelo.  alatin america.  alatin american cinema.  alatin american history.  alinguistic play.  aluis sandrini.  amodernization.  anew latin american cinema.  anini marshall.  apopularity.  aspatiotemporal emplacement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029684840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969162/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles